05902nam a22008175i 9780292795433DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927954337 a10.7560/7134752doi  a(DE-B1597)588118  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aE99.M6815bA52 2007 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a97600aAncient Objects and Sacred Realms :bInterpretations of Mississippian Iconography /ced. by F. Kent, III Reilly, F. Kent, James F. Garber. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Some Cosmological Motifs in the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex -- t3. The Petaloid Motif: A Celestial Symbolic Locative in the Shell Art of Spiro -- t4. On the Identity of the Birdman within Mississippian Period Art and Iconography -- t5. The Great Serpent in Eastern North America -- t6. Identification of a Moth/Butterfly Supernatural in Mississippian Art -- t7. Ritual, Medicine, and the War Trophy Iconographic Theme in the Mississippian Southeast -- t8. The ‘‘Path of Souls’’: Some Death Imagery in the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex -- t9. Sequencing the Braden Style within Mississippian Period Art and Iconography -- t10. Osage Texts and Cahokia Data -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween AD 900-1600, the native peoples of the Mississippi River Valley and other areas of the Eastern Woodlands of the United States conceived and executed one of the greatest artistic traditions of the Precolumbian Americas. Created in the media of copper, shell, stone, clay, and wood, and incised or carved with a complex set of symbols and motifs, this seven-hundred-year-old artistic tradition functioned within a multiethnic landscape centered on communities dominated by earthen mounds and plazas. Previous researchers have referred to this material as the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex (SECC). This groundbreaking volume brings together ten essays by leading anthropologists, archaeologists, and art historians, who analyze the iconography of Mississippian art in order to reconstruct the ritual activities, cosmological vision, and ideology of these ancient precursors to several groups of contemporary Native Americans. Significantly, the authors correlate archaeological, ethnographic, and art historical data that illustrate the stylistic differences within Mississippian art as well as the numerous changes that occur through time. The research also demonstrates the inadequacy of the SECC label, since Mississippian art is not limited to the Southeast and reflects stylistic changes over time among several linked but distinct religious traditions. The term Mississippian Iconographic Interaction Sphere (MIIS) more adequately describes the corpus of this Mississippian art. Most important, the authors illustrate the overarching nature of the ancient Native American religious system, as a creation unique to the native American cultures of the eastern United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericazMississippi River ValleyxAntiquities. 0aIndians of North AmericazSouthern StatesxAntiquities. 0aMississippian art. 0aMississippian culture. 0aSupernatural in art. 0aSymbolism in artzMississippi River Valley. 0aSymbolism in artzSouthern States. 0aSymbolism in art. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aBrown, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDye, David H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranke, Judith A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul